an who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|GA|8}} since 2011. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\nScott's father, Jim, is an orthopedic surgeon and his mother, Becky, is a teacher in the public school system. Scott graduated from the [[University of Georgia]] with a B.B.A. in risk management and insurance. He passed the Series 7 Exam.<ref>{{cite web|title=Austin Scott \u2013 Biography|url=http://www.austinscott.house.gov/full-biography/}}</ref>\n\nScott is president of the Southern Group, LLC and a partner in Lockett Station Group, LLC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legis.state.ga.us/legis/2009_10/house/bios/scottAustin/scottAustinBio.htm|title=Representative Austin Scott|publisher=Legis.state.ga.us|date=|accessdate=2010-08-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090322182235/http://www.legis.state.ga.us/legis/2009_10/house/bios/scottAustin/scottAustinBio.htm|archive-date=2009-03-22|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Georgia legislature==\nScott was first elected to the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] at the age of 26. He was the chairman of the Governmental Affairs Committee. He also served on the Appropriations, Rules, and Ways and Means Committee, where he was the chairman of the Public Policy Subcommittee. The District he represented consists of [[Tift County, Georgia|Tift]] and [[Turner County, Georgia|Turner]] counties.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n====2010====\n[[File:Austin fire.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Austin Scott meets with members of the Carrollton, GA fire department on July 20, 2009 during the Walk of Georgia.]]\n\nScott challenged Democratic incumbent [[Jim Marshall (Georgia politician)|Jim Marshall]] in Georgia's eighth congressional district. He defeated Marshall in the general election on November 2, 2010, with 53% of the vote to Marshall's 47%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/2010/maps/#/House/2010/GA|title=2010 Election results|publisher=Politico|date=2010-11-05|accessdate=2011-08-09}}</ref>\n\nScott originally planned to campaign for Governor of Georgia, announcing his campaign in January 2009. He made headlines for walking more than 1,000 miles around the state in his \"Walk of Georgia\",<ref>[http://walkingwithaustin.com \"Walk of Georgia\"]</ref> introducing a bill to abolish tolls on [[Georgia State Route 400|Georgia 400]], and leading the charge in pressuring Georgia State Attorney General [[Thurbert Baker]] to file a lawsuit against the federal government over the controversial [[Health care reform in the United States|health care reform bill]] passed in March 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tiftongazette.com/local/x323702349/Scott-plans-1-000-mile-Walk-Around-Georgia|title=Scott plans 1,000-mile 'Walk Around Georgia'|publisher=Tifton Gazette|date=2009-06-24|accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://swgapolitics.com/index/2009/08/29/austin-scott-completes-walk-of-georgia|title=Austin Scott Completes Walk of Georgia|publisher=SWGA Politics|date=2009-08-29|accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Badertscher|first=Nancy|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/georgia-politics-elections/abolish-ga-400-toll-397683.html|title=Abolish Ga. 400 toll, candidate's bill proposes|publisher=ajc.com|date=2010-03-23|accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Tharpe|first=Jim|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/georgia-politics-elections/republican-lawmaker-wants-state-407164.html|title=Republican lawmaker wants state to \u2018direct' Baker to sue over health care|publisher=ajc.com|date=2010-03-26|accessdate=2010-08-22}}</ref> In April 2010, Scott withdrew from the race for Governor to instead run for U.S. Congress.\n\nIn 2010, Scott signed a pledge sponsored by [[Americans for Prosperity]] promising to vote against any global warming legislation that would raise taxes.<ref>http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2010/06/scott-austin.pdf</ref>\n\n====2012====\n[[File:Austin Scott, Official Portrait, 112th Congress.jpg|thumb|Scott's freshman portrait]]\nThe Georgia General Assembly redrew the 8th district after the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. Notably, most of [[Macon, Georgia|Macon]] and surrounding [[Bibb County, Georgia|Bibb County]] (except for a sliver in the north) were drawn into the neighboring [[Georgia's 2nd congressional district|2nd district]]. Macon had been the heart of the 8th and its predecessors for more than a century. To make up for the loss of population, the General Assembly pushed the 8th all the way to the [[Florida]] border, adding [[Thomasville, Georgia|Thomasville]] and most of [[Valdosta, Georgia|Valdosta]] from the old 2nd. The old 8th already had a significant Republican lean, with a [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] of R+10. However, the new 8th has a CPVI of R+15, making it the 11th most Republican district in the [[Eastern Time Zone]] and one of the most Republican districts in the country.\n\nScott was unopposed in both the primary and general elections.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/GA/42277/112424/en/summary.html|title=GA \u2013 Election Results|accessdate=November 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\nScott was unopposed for a third term.\n\n====2016====\nIn 2016, Scott faced a Democratic opponent for the first time since his initial run for the seat when private investigator James Neal Harris declared for the race. Scott turned back this challenge fairly easily, taking 67.6% of the vote and carrying every county in the district.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=801578|title=Our Campaigns - GA District 08 Race - Nov 08, 2016|website=www.ourcampaigns.com|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Agriculture|Committee on Agriculture]]'''\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management|Subcommittee on General Farm Commodities and Risk Management]]\n** [[United States House Agriculture Subcommittee on Rural Development, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture|Subcommittee on Rural Development, Research, Biotechnology, and Foreign Agriculture]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Military Personnel|Subcommittee on Military Personnel]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Readiness|Subcommittee on Readiness]]\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Strategic Forces|Subcommittee on Strategic Forces]]\n\n'''Caucus Memberships'''\n* '''[[Republican Study Committee]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Member List|author=|url=https://rsc-walker.house.gov/|format=|publisher=Republican Study Committee|date=|accessdate=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n* Congressional Cement Caucus\n*[[United States Congressional International Conservation Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Our Members|author=|url=https://royce.house.gov/internationalconservation/members.html|format=|publisher=U.S. House of Representatives International Conservation Caucus |date=|accessdate=5 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n\nScott is in favor of [[capital punishment]].<ref name=\"OTIScott\">{{cite web|title=Austin Scott on the Issues|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Austin_Scott.htm|website=On The Issues|accessdate=25 December 2017}}</ref> He opposes [[gun control]].<ref name=\"OTIScott\"/>\n\nScott is in favor of a [[Balanced budget amendment]].<ref name=\"OTIScott\"/> He voted in favor of the [[Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017]].<ref name=\"Almukhtar\">{{cite web|last1=Almukhtar|first1=Sarah|title=How Each House Member Voted on the Tax Bill|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/12/19/us/politics/tax-bill-house-live-vote.html?_r=0|website=The New York Times|accessdate=25 December 2017|date=19 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nScott is [[Anti-abortion movements|opposed to abortion]] and believes that human life begins at conception.<ref name=\"OTIScott\"/>\n\nHe has a \"D\" rating from marijuana legalization advocacy organization the [[National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws]] (NORML) for his voting history regarding [[cannabis]]-related issues.<ref name=\"NORML\">{{cite web|title=Georgia Scorecard|url=http://norml.org/congressional-scorecard/georgia|website=NORML|accessdate=25 December 2017|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nScott opposes [[same-sex marriage]] and is in favor of a [[Federal Marriage Amendment]].<ref name=\"OTIScott\"/> He voted against the 2013 renewal of the [[Violence Against Women Act]].<ref name=\"OTIScott\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nScott resides in Tifton with his wife, Vivien, and son, Wells. The Scotts are members of First Baptist Church of Tifton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.legis.state.ga.us/legis/2009_10/house/bios/scottAustin/scottAustinBio.htm |title=Representative Austin Scott |publisher=Legis.state.ga.us |date= |accessdate=2010-08-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090322182235/http://www.legis.state.ga.us/legis/2009_10/house/bios/scottAustin/scottAustinBio.htm |archive-date=2009-03-22 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref name=Baptist>{{cite news|last=Staff|first=|title=Ten Southern Baptists sworn in as new reps.|url=http://www.bpnews.net/bpnews.asp?id=34378|accessdate=25 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226010629/http://www.bpnews.net/34378|archivedate=25 December 2014|newspaper=Baptist Press|date=5 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons cat}}\n* [http://austinscott.house.gov/ Congressman Austin Scott] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.scottforga.com/ Austin Scott for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Austin_Scott_%5BR-8%5D|Austin Scott}}\n* {{C-SPAN|austinscott03}}\n* {{CongLink